[1] Russia (Chelyabinsk)
Date: Sun 23 Oct 2005
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters alertnet, 22 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L22123226.htm>

More bird flu cases found in Russia
---------------------------------------
Russian vets have found bird flu in a village in the southern Urals
and suspected an outbreak of the disease in a neighboring region, the
emergency ministry said on Saturday [22 Oct 2005].
In the village of Sunaly in the Chelyabinsk region in the southern
Urals, 31 chickens died, and local authorities found bird flu in 6
samples out of 12, an emergency ministry official in Moscow told
Reuters. [See map
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/RS/13/Sunaly.html>].
A Chelyabinsk emergency ministry official said vets had found the
H5N1 strain and suspected that the infection came with migrating birds.
"There are 1060 birds in the village," the official said. "They will
all be killed. A quarantine was imposed from today. Vaccination of
all 89 people in the village will start on Monday [24 Oct 2005]."
Authorities are also investigating another suspected outbreak in
Russia's Altai region.
The Moscow emergency ministry official said bird flu was suspected in
a village in the Altai region, close to the Kazakh border, where 59
birds died in the village of Pokrovka on Friday [21 Oct 2005]. [See map
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/RS/4/Pokrovka8.html>].
"A quarantine zone has been imposed, although we have only found
antibodies for bird flu in the preliminary tests. The final decision
on whether it is bird flu and what will be done will only be taken on
Monday [24 Oct 2005]," the official said.
Moscow confirmed on Wednesday [19 Oct 2005] an outbreak of H5N1 in
the Tula region, some 200 km (125 miles) south of the Russian capital.
Russia has been fighting bird flu since mid-July 2005 and has killed
more than 600 000 domestic fowl.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Another newswire on the same date by Interfax included additional
details on the outbreak in Sunaly: "33 birds, among them turkeys,
ducks, and chickens, have died at 2 individual farms in the village
of Sunaly. There are a total of 26 individual farms in the village." - Mod.AS]
