[2] Cross reactive immunity
Date: Sun 23 Oct 2005
From: Wu Wei <wu16wei@yahoo.com>

Re: Archive Number 20051016.3018
-----------------------------------------
ProMED-mail posting 20051016.3018, Avian influenza - Eurasia (13):
H5N1, item [2] "Agriculture ministry buys 8 million doses of avian
flu vaccine," included the following statement from Israel:
"Officials believe that a dose of the regular seasonal flu vaccine
may reduce the incidence of sickness in case of an avian flu epidemic."
Given all the studies done about cross-reactive immunity, the
question needs to be answered whether a regular flu vaccination might
provide some small degree of protection.
--
Wu Wei
<wu16wei@yahoo.com>
[We guess the citing might reflect a misunderstanding between
officials and the press. No cross protection against H5N1 is known to
be conferred by vaccination with the regular human vaccine. For the
composition of the trivalent vaccine recommended for use during the
2005-2006 influenza season (northern hemisphere winter), see 20050915.2726.
Additional or different views are welcome.
Propagating human vaccination with the regular influenza vaccine in
areas affected by avian influenza is based upon the Dutch experience
during the H7N7 outbreak of 2003. They vaccinated with the regular
influenza vaccine persons exposed to infected poultry. Their
reasoning was the wish to prevent mixed, simultaneous infections of
humans by both human and avian influenza viruses, a constellation
which might lead to virus reassortment; see 20030501.1092. - Mod.AS]
******
[3] UK, Sweden, Croatia
Date: Sun 23 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AP via The London Free Press, 23 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://lfpress.ca/newsstand/News/International/2005/10/23/pf-1274440.html>

Scientists were conducting tests yesterday [22 Oct 2005] to determine
whether bird flu cases discovered in Britain, Sweden and Croatia are
the lethal strain that has killed more than 60 people, as countries
around the world scrambled to halt the spread of the virus.
Congo joined a growing list of African countries to ban imports of
livestock and poultry from countries affected by bird flu, and Russia
recorded a new outbreak of the disease in a region of the Ural mountains.
In Croatia, the Agriculture Ministry said the country's 1st cases of
avian flu were confirmed Friday [21 Oct 2005] in 6 swans found dead
in a national park in the east of the country. British officials said
a parrot from the South American country Suriname died of the disease
while in quarantine. It was Britain's 1st confirmed case of bird flu
since 1992.
In both cases, tests were underway at a British lab to determine
whether the birds had the deadly H5N1 strain, which has devastated
poultry stocks across Asia and killed 61 people in 2 years. The
strain was recently found in birds in Russia, Turkey and Romania.
Sweden's National Veterinary Institute said yesterday [22 Oct 2005] a
case of bird flu had been confirmed in one of 4 ducks found dead
Friday [21 Oct 2005] in Eskilstuna, about 100 km west of the capital,
Stockholm. Officials said it would take days to determine whether it
was the H5N1 strain.
The European Union, which has ordered restrictions on bird markets
and urged countries to present a program of vaccination for zoo
birds, said Friday [21 Oct 2005] it was preparing to ban poultry
imports from Croatia.
In Britain, chief veterinarian Debby Reynolds said the country's
disease-free status was not affected by the case of bird flu, because
the parrot died while in quarantine. She said the incident
demonstrated the importance of Britain's tough quarantine system.
Reynolds said the parrot, which died last week [3rd week October
2005], arrived in Britain in September 2005 and was being held in a
biosecure quarantine unit along with a consignment of birds from Taiwan.
Britain said it was in contact with officials in Suriname and Taiwan
as it sought to determine where the bird contacted the virus. If the
parrot was infected in Suriname, it would be the 1st confirmed case
of serious bird flu in the Western Hemisphere. Mild forms that do not
threaten people have been found in Colombia and Brazil.
Congo's Health Minister, Emil Bongeli, said Friday [21 Oct 2005] his
government had banned the import of live birds, pigs and livestock
from countries affected by H5N1. Other African countries have also
banned poultry imports, including Senegal, Uganda and neighboring
Congo-Brazzaville.
--
