[4] Sweden
Date: Sun 23 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Medicalnewstoday, 23 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/healthnews.php?newsid=32505#>
Duck in Sweden had bird flu
----------------------------
Sweden's National Veterinary Institute confirmed that a wild duck
which had been found dead in the Swedish countryside (Eskilstuna) had
bird flu (avian influenza). 7 dead ducks were found, 4 were tested
and one came up positive for bird flu. It will be a few days before
we know whether the duck died from the more virulent bird flu strain
H5N1. [See map <http://www.fallingrain.com/world/SW/18/Eskilstuna.html>].
Several European countries have now reported cases of bird flu: The
United Kingdom (a quarantined parrot from Suriname; see commentary),
Romania, Greece, Croatia (6 swans), Russia and Turkey.
The infected birds in Russia, Turkey, Greece and Romania were
carrying the H5N1 strain. Lab tests have not been completed on the
other countries to see whether their birds had the lethal strain.
The United Kingdom government is calling for a ban on all wild bird
imports into the EU. The EU only bans the imports of live birds from
countries that have had cases of bird flu.
Many countries around the world are banning the imports of live birds
from infected countries
--
